<!-- Why CI -->
<h1>why practise <em class="keyword">continuous integration</em>?</h1>
<p>
  The practise of
  <a title="Martin Fowler's description of the practice of continuous integration"
     href="http://www.martinfowler.com/articles/continuousIntegration.html"
     ><em class="keyword">continuous integration</em></a>
  is all about increasing productivity and reducing risk.
  An <em class="keyword">automated build server</em> combined with an
  automated <em class="keyword">unit test suite</em> constantly monitors
  the quality of your source code, leading to:
</p>
<ul class="benefits">
  <li><em>increased developer productivity</em>
    no more time is wasted debugging integration issues;
  </li>
  <li><em>lower development cost</em>
    problems are found earlier, making them cheaper to fix;
  </li>
  <li><em>higher visibility of progress</em>
    through constant monitoring and feedback.
  </li>
</ul>
<p>
  Read more about the benefits of a <em class="keyword">continuous build server</em> in
  our <a title="benefits of continuous integration :: pulse continuous integration server"
	 href="/products/pulse/articles/">articles</a>.
</p>


